 Then it is time to freshen up your CV, motivation letter and your LinkedIn by
meeting our expert panel of 4 Taiwan-based professionals.

town. 

 Please register on ACCUPASS on the event page.

recruiters?
5. How to genuinely talk about your motivations for a role.

28th. https://www.facebook.com/events/1373248406185245/

I recently hit my three-year mark in Taiwan back in September 2019. For anyone
reading this that hasn't met me, yes, I've only lived in Taiwan for three years.
That's still a tad shocking for people that hear me speak Mandarin and hear my
thoughts on societal topics. I suppose I haven't been around long enough to get
a firm grasp on Taiwanese society, but I feel like I have a better grasp than a
lot of long-time "expats" and foreigners.

 So, I hit my third year mark, and my one comment in all those three years I
need to address is the question of "why are you sweaty?"

 Because Taiwan is so goddamn hot.

text:
If Korean Fish is recalled in 高雄, that might be a huge both a blow and relief to
the KMT.

 In the short-term, it'll only be another bruise to their wounds that they're
licking after the latest election.

 In the long-run, it'll allow the KMT to distance themselves from his mess. If
the KMT doesn't reorganize and question what they stand for, they face the
reality of becoming obsolete. 

 All in all, the last two elections have shown a clear mandate from the people
to be more cautious towards China, and to be treated with respect. 

 To me, Taiwanese standing up for themselves isn't an issue of "let's not upset
China" but more about taking having the self-respect to make decisions without
worrying what a neighboring totalitarian government thinks. 

 That makes Taiwan more politically stronger than most of multinational
businesses and countries in the world.

 I applaud everyone in Taiwan for making a stand that the rest of the world
should be making. Mutual respect.
